{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"3b8c4c38-d497-4eb0-bf9c-7fdf91ac2314","content":"`SafeAreaEdges=\"None\"` handles the **iOS** safe area, but you likely also need to address **Android** and possibly **Shell chrome**. Here's what's typically missing:\n\n**1. Android edge-to-edge** — System bars still occlude content unless you opt in:\n\n```csharp\n// MauiProgram.cs\nbuilder.ConfigureLifecycleEvents(events =>\n{\n#if ANDROID\n    events.AddAndroid(android => android.OnCreate((activity, _) =>\n    {\n        activity.Window.SetStatusBarColor(Android.Graphics.Color.Transparent);\n        activity.Window.SetNavigationBarColor(Android.Graphics.Color.Transparent);\n        AndroidX.Core.View.WindowCompat.SetDecorFitsSystemWindows(activity.Window, false);\n    }));\n#endif\n});\n```\n\n> On .NET 10 targeting Android 15+, edge-to-edge is enforced automatically, but you still need transparent bar colors.\n\n**2. Hide Shell chrome** (if using `Shell`):\n\n```xml\n<ContentPage\n    Shell.NavBarIsVisible=\"False\"\n    Shell.TabBarIsVisible=\"False\"\n    SafeAreaEdges=\"None\">\n```\n\n**3. Image fill** — make sure the image actually stretches edge-to-edge:\n\n```xml\n<Image Source=\"photo.jpg\"\n       Aspect=\"AspectFill\"\n       HorizontalOptions=\"Fill\"\n       VerticalOptions=\"Fill\" />\n```\n\n**Putting it all together** in your page XAML:\n\n```xml\n<ContentPage xmlns=\"http://schemas.microsoft.com/dotnet/2021/maui\"\n             Shell.NavBarIsVisible=\"False\"\n             Shell.TabBarIsVisible=\"False\"\n             SafeAreaEdges=\"None\">\n    <Image Source=\"photo.jpg\"\n           Aspect=\"AspectFill\"\n           HorizontalOptions=\"Fill\"\n           VerticalOptions=\"Fill\" />\n</ContentPage>\n```\n\nThe most commonly overlooked piece is step **1** — without `SetDecorFitsSystemWindows(false)` on Android, the system bars reserve space regardless of your XAML settings.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"5f3eebef-28db-4470-a06b-867956ae3072","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is working with .NET MAUI and wants to achieve edge-to-edge/full-screen content that goes behind the status bar and navigation bar. They've tried setting `SafeAreaEdges=\"None\"` on the ContentPage but the image still has padding.\n\nThis is a common .NET MAUI question. Let me think about what's needed:\n\nIn .NET MAUI (.NET 10), to achieve edge-to-edge content:\n\n1. `SafeAreaEdges` - controls whether the page respects safe area insets. Setting it to `None` should allow content to go behind system bars.\n\n2. But there's more to it - you also need to make sure the system bars are transparent/translucent so content can actually render behind them.\n\n\n3. The padding could be coming from multiple sources depending on the platform. On iOS, `SafeAreaEdges` is the primary control, but on Android, edge-to-edge mode needs to be explicitly enabled, and there might be additional layout constraints or window insets being applied that are separate from the safe area concept. If they're using Shell navigation, that's likely adding extra chrome they need to hide with `Shell.NavBarIsVisible=\"False\"` and `Shell.TabBarIsVisible=\"False\"`. On Android specifically, they'll need to make the status and navigation bars transparent, which in .NET 10 might involve `Window.StatusBarBehavior` or platform-specific configuration. The `SafeAreaEdges` property could help control safe area behavior, but availability varies by version. older Android versions need explicit edge-to-edge enabling. The main fixes are setting transparent system bars on Android, hiding the Shell navigation chrome if needed, and using `AspectFill` on the Image control to fill the screen properly. Since this is general MAUI knowledge rather than a codebase-specific issue, I can work through the solution directly. I'm realizing there's some overlap here between the older `Page.UseSafeArea` API and the newer `SafeAreaEdges` approach. For Android specifically, the solution involves disabling system window decorations to enable edge-to-edge rendering, either through platform-specific code that calls `SetDecorFitsSystemWindows(false)` or relying on the default edge-to-edge behavior in .NET 10 targeting Android 15+. The cross-platform approach for iOS uses the platform-specific configuration to disable safe area constraints, while Android needs that window-level adjustment.\n\nLooking at what the user's actually trying to solve, it's probably one of three things: the system bars aren't transparent on Android, the Shell navigation chrome is still taking up space, or the image scaling isn't set to fill the available space properly. I should give them a straightforward, actionable answer focused on the most likely culprit.","outputTokens":2180,"requestId":"1011:325178:15AD2E9:185F19E:69FD3748"},"id":"db98c667-e97d-4f90-aebf-74ed46d503c1","timestamp":"2026-05-08T01:08:04.625Z","parentId":"04b3ea78-ae80-4358-94f3-cdcc6726b1cf"}
